1
00:00:00,180 --> 00:00:00,990
Hello everyone.

2
00:00:01,080 --> 00:00:01,560
Welcome.

3
00:00:02,310 --> 00:00:04,200
I want to talk about something.

4
00:00:04,200 --> 00:00:08,340
A lot of us in the enterprise
analytics space keep running into.

5
00:00:08,970 --> 00:00:12,990
Our design systems just aren't
keeping up with the complexity

6
00:00:12,990 --> 00:00:14,130
of what we are building.

7
00:00:14,910 --> 00:00:20,220
By the end of this talk, I want to leave
you with a framework, a seven layer model

8
00:00:20,520 --> 00:00:25,950
that gives us a much better way to think
about building and scaling these systems.

9
00:00:26,450 --> 00:00:27,740
But before we get into it.

10
00:00:28,549 --> 00:00:30,049
Let me introduce myself.

11
00:00:30,650 --> 00:00:33,500
I'm Sonali Creative
Director at LB Networks.

12
00:00:33,560 --> 00:00:39,019
I have spent over a decade working
across enterprise platforms, so what

13
00:00:39,019 --> 00:00:44,750
I'm about to share with you comes from
real experience watching design systems

14
00:00:44,750 --> 00:00:50,120
work, watching them break and figuring
out what it actually takes to scale them.

15
00:00:50,540 --> 00:00:55,580
When the data is huge, the users are
diverse and the stakes are very high.

16
00:00:56,180 --> 00:00:57,110
Let's get into it.

17
00:00:57,610 --> 00:00:59,650
Alright, so let's start with the problem.

18
00:01:00,190 --> 00:01:04,840
If you have worked on any enterprise
analytics platform, whether that

19
00:01:04,840 --> 00:01:09,310
is telecom, financial services,
healthcare, or infrastructure, you

20
00:01:09,310 --> 00:01:12,310
have already seen these patterns First.

21
00:01:12,370 --> 00:01:17,920
Fragmentation, different teams build the
same charts and dashboards from scratch.

22
00:01:18,340 --> 00:01:22,540
There's no shared component
library that actually handles

23
00:01:22,660 --> 00:01:24,040
what analytics teams need.

24
00:01:24,540 --> 00:01:29,550
So what end up ends up happening
is you end up with a five

25
00:01:29,550 --> 00:01:33,180
different version of the same line
chart, all slightly different.

26
00:01:33,680 --> 00:01:36,020
Second visual drift.

27
00:01:36,650 --> 00:01:41,990
When there's no shared systems, every
team starts making their own decisions.

28
00:01:42,470 --> 00:01:47,870
Things like colors, scales, access
labels, how to display thresholds.

29
00:01:48,845 --> 00:01:53,405
The result is that two dashboards in
the same product can look like they

30
00:01:53,405 --> 00:01:55,385
were built by two different companies.

31
00:01:55,655 --> 00:01:58,445
They don't sync together at all.

32
00:01:58,945 --> 00:02:01,345
And third, governance gaps.

33
00:02:01,945 --> 00:02:04,975
Nobody owns the definition of a metric.

34
00:02:05,245 --> 00:02:07,585
Nobody owns the versioning of a component.

35
00:02:08,275 --> 00:02:13,195
Access control is bolted on after the
fact instead of being part of the system.

36
00:02:13,825 --> 00:02:17,095
And when something breaks
or changes, there's no clear

37
00:02:17,095 --> 00:02:18,535
path for who's responsible.

38
00:02:19,035 --> 00:02:20,655
These are in small problems.

39
00:02:20,925 --> 00:02:25,785
They compound over time and they get
worse the bigger your platform gets.

40
00:02:26,475 --> 00:02:31,455
So it's better to solve from the
very beginning than wait until later.

41
00:02:31,955 --> 00:02:37,115
Now, the standard answer in our
industry has been design systems

42
00:02:37,265 --> 00:02:38,765
and design systems are great.

43
00:02:39,620 --> 00:02:42,290
The typical model has three layers.

44
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:48,290
You start with primitives, which
is your design, tokens, colors,

45
00:02:48,290 --> 00:02:53,030
spacing, typography, the raw
values of your design system.

46
00:02:53,530 --> 00:02:58,270
In the middle, we have components,
and components are things like

47
00:02:58,720 --> 00:03:05,080
buttons, inputs, cards, models, the
reusable pieces that actually build

48
00:03:05,140 --> 00:03:07,180
the whole component, whole library.

49
00:03:08,095 --> 00:03:16,645
And the last is patterns or semantics,
how those components come together into

50
00:03:16,645 --> 00:03:19,675
a page layout and interaction flows.

51
00:03:20,175 --> 00:03:25,335
This model has been incredibly
successful for consumer apps.

52
00:03:25,755 --> 00:03:30,255
If you are building a social network,
an e-commerce site, a SaaS tool,

53
00:03:30,795 --> 00:03:32,755
three layers will take you very far.

54
00:03:33,255 --> 00:03:37,005
It gives you consistency,
reusability, and a shared language

55
00:03:37,005 --> 00:03:38,805
between design and engineering.

56
00:03:39,305 --> 00:03:43,775
But enterprise analytics
is a whole different beast.

57
00:03:44,275 --> 00:03:47,485
Now, here's where it all falls apart.

58
00:03:47,985 --> 00:03:48,405
Tables.

59
00:03:48,410 --> 00:03:49,820
Tables break at scale.

60
00:03:50,180 --> 00:03:54,200
Your standard table component was
designed for maybe a few hundred rows.

61
00:03:54,635 --> 00:04:00,305
But enterprise platforms routinely deal
with hundreds of thousands, even millions

62
00:04:00,305 --> 00:04:05,885
of rows, virtualization, streaming,
lazy loading, and none of that is built

63
00:04:05,885 --> 00:04:07,865
into a typical design system table.

64
00:04:08,365 --> 00:04:12,535
So what ends up happening is team
builds their own solution, and

65
00:04:13,015 --> 00:04:16,404
now you have lost the whole point
of having a shared design system.

66
00:04:16,904 --> 00:04:19,094
Visuals get unreadable.

67
00:04:19,950 --> 00:04:25,470
A chart that looks clean and elegant with
a hundred data points becomes unreadable

68
00:04:25,470 --> 00:04:27,900
mess with a hundred thousand points.

69
00:04:28,410 --> 00:04:33,180
The three layer model has no option
about aggregation strategies,

70
00:04:33,390 --> 00:04:35,880
sampling, or progressive disclosure.

71
00:04:36,510 --> 00:04:40,290
It just gives you a chart
component and wishes you good luck.

72
00:04:40,890 --> 00:04:43,200
Scalability is the core gap.

73
00:04:43,770 --> 00:04:47,490
The three layer model was
built to optimize for visual

74
00:04:47,490 --> 00:04:49,380
polish and interaction design.

75
00:04:49,920 --> 00:04:52,980
It was not built to
think about data volume.

76
00:04:53,640 --> 00:05:01,080
Query delays are the cost of rendering
a million row data set in the browser,

77
00:05:02,010 --> 00:05:07,890
and maybe the most frustrating part
is there's nothing drop in and go.

78
00:05:08,130 --> 00:05:11,400
You can't just grab a component
off the shelf and have it

79
00:05:11,460 --> 00:05:12,900
work with your data pipeline.

80
00:05:13,545 --> 00:05:18,915
Your metric layer or access controls
teams end up stitching libraries

81
00:05:18,915 --> 00:05:24,725
together by hand, and what you get
is something which is very hard to

82
00:05:24,725 --> 00:05:31,775
maintain, is inconsistent and doesn't
flow together with your entire product.

83
00:05:32,275 --> 00:05:37,225
We know why it breaks, so now let's
talk about how to actually fix it.

84
00:05:37,855 --> 00:05:41,395
So what I'm proposing
is a seven layer model.

85
00:05:42,055 --> 00:05:46,825
It keeps the foundation of the three
layers we already know, but extends it

86
00:05:47,094 --> 00:05:52,435
with four additional layers that address
the realities of enterprise analytics.

87
00:05:53,305 --> 00:05:56,275
Let me walk you through the
stack from bottom to top.

88
00:05:56,755 --> 00:06:00,625
The bottom two tokens and UI
components are familiar from the

89
00:06:00,985 --> 00:06:03,715
previous three layer design system.

90
00:06:04,215 --> 00:06:10,844
That's the most design systems already
cover, but layers three through seven

91
00:06:10,935 --> 00:06:12,705
are where the real work happens.

92
00:06:13,205 --> 00:06:14,974
Let me take you through each one of them.

93
00:06:15,474 --> 00:06:18,384
Layer one is your design token foundation.

94
00:06:18,835 --> 00:06:22,794
This is where everything starts,
the atomic values that every

95
00:06:22,794 --> 00:06:28,194
other layer references to, but
for analytics, tokens need to go

96
00:06:28,194 --> 00:06:30,864
beyond the usual colors and spacing.

97
00:06:31,344 --> 00:06:36,265
You need dedicated data visualization,
color palettes, sequential scales,

98
00:06:36,294 --> 00:06:41,544
diversion scales, categorical
scales, purpose built for

99
00:06:41,544 --> 00:06:43,884
readability in charts and dashboards.

100
00:06:44,754 --> 00:06:46,854
You need density modes.

101
00:06:47,304 --> 00:06:53,644
A dashboard packs much more information
into a smaller space than a typical mobile

102
00:06:53,644 --> 00:06:56,614
application or any other app screen.

103
00:06:57,334 --> 00:07:00,424
Your token should adapt titrate, spacing.

104
00:07:00,754 --> 00:07:04,534
Smaller type, denser layout
depending on the context.

105
00:07:05,164 --> 00:07:09,574
You also need semantic tokens
that carry meaning not just blue

106
00:07:09,574 --> 00:07:12,034
and red, but threshold exceeded.

107
00:07:12,064 --> 00:07:13,354
Anomaly detected.

108
00:07:13,804 --> 00:07:14,824
Target met.

109
00:07:15,244 --> 00:07:19,504
The token layer should encode
intent, not just appearance.

110
00:07:20,044 --> 00:07:24,604
And these tokens should compile
to every platform you ship on.

111
00:07:25,294 --> 00:07:29,809
CSS, iOS, Android, Figma,
from a single source of truth.

112
00:07:30,679 --> 00:07:33,199
One definition, many outputs.

113
00:07:33,829 --> 00:07:41,179
Layer two is UI components, things like
buttons, inputs, selects, models, tabs,

114
00:07:41,179 --> 00:07:43,639
breadcrumbs, the standard toolkit.

115
00:07:44,299 --> 00:07:49,609
This layer is important and it should
be built entirely on top of your tokens.

116
00:07:49,909 --> 00:07:51,349
No hardcoded values.

117
00:07:51,619 --> 00:07:57,229
Every components pull its own
colors, spacing type from layer one.

118
00:07:57,729 --> 00:08:00,429
But here's the key thing to
understand about this layer.

119
00:08:00,849 --> 00:08:03,489
These components are unaware of data.

120
00:08:04,269 --> 00:08:08,259
A button doesn't know whether it's
filtering a million rows or submitting

121
00:08:08,259 --> 00:08:14,399
a form and input doesn't know if it's
selecting a metric for consumer products.

122
00:08:14,489 --> 00:08:20,310
This layer plus tokens is
usually enough for analytics.

123
00:08:20,429 --> 00:08:21,749
It's just the starting point.

124
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:24,210
This is where most design systems stop.

125
00:08:24,705 --> 00:08:26,024
We need to keep going.

126
00:08:26,524 --> 00:08:29,014
Layer three is where
things get interesting.

127
00:08:29,614 --> 00:08:34,865
These are data components, UI elements
that know they're handling data at scale.

128
00:08:35,365 --> 00:08:39,865
This is your virtualized table
that can handle a million rows

129
00:08:39,865 --> 00:08:41,454
without choking the browser.

130
00:08:41,905 --> 00:08:46,074
This is your query builder,
your filter panel metric

131
00:08:46,135 --> 00:08:48,025
picker, your dimension selector.

132
00:08:48,564 --> 00:08:51,050
These are components that
understand data types.

133
00:08:51,670 --> 00:08:55,630
That know how to paginate
stream and lazy load.

134
00:08:56,130 --> 00:08:58,079
They are stateful by design.

135
00:08:58,439 --> 00:09:03,420
They handle loading states, empty
states, partial data error boundaries.

136
00:09:03,839 --> 00:09:05,609
They don't just render data.

137
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:10,290
They manage the whole life cycle
of getting it, displaying it, and

138
00:09:10,290 --> 00:09:16,339
recovering when things go wrong and
the support personalization users

139
00:09:16,339 --> 00:09:18,680
can configure columns, save views.

140
00:09:19,054 --> 00:09:22,924
Set defaults without breaking
the shared definition underneath.

141
00:09:23,224 --> 00:09:27,994
This is the layer that most
directly addresses the table.

142
00:09:27,994 --> 00:09:29,554
Break at scale problem.

143
00:09:29,974 --> 00:09:33,214
If your design system doesn't
have data where components.

144
00:09:33,619 --> 00:09:37,099
Your team will build their own,
and then you have lost consist.

145
00:09:37,599 --> 00:09:42,040
Okay, next is layer four, which
is visualization primitives.

146
00:09:42,729 --> 00:09:45,939
And I want to be clear,
this is not a chart library.

147
00:09:46,030 --> 00:09:48,040
This is the layer below the charts.

148
00:09:48,640 --> 00:09:52,770
These are the building blocks that
charts are assembled from things

149
00:09:52,770 --> 00:09:56,729
like scales, legends, grits.

150
00:09:56,819 --> 00:09:56,849
Tooltips.

151
00:09:57,349 --> 00:10:02,779
These are the composable pieces that are
put together to create a line chart, a bar

152
00:10:02,779 --> 00:10:05,509
chart, a scatter plot, or even a heat map.

153
00:10:06,009 --> 00:10:11,109
This layer defines your visual
encodings, how data maps to position,

154
00:10:11,410 --> 00:10:17,020
color, size, and shape, and it does
so with accessibility, built in

155
00:10:17,290 --> 00:10:21,790
colorblind, safe palettes, pattern
fallbacks, screen reader support.

156
00:10:22,290 --> 00:10:26,700
It also handles the hard problem of
what to show when you have more data

157
00:10:26,730 --> 00:10:33,090
than pixels, aggregation rules, sampling
strategies, level of detail switching.

158
00:10:34,020 --> 00:10:38,190
These decisions shouldn't be
made ad hoc by individual teams.

159
00:10:38,460 --> 00:10:43,620
They should be encoded in the
system, and it includes interaction

160
00:10:43,620 --> 00:10:47,640
perimeters, things like Zoom, brush pan.

161
00:10:48,224 --> 00:10:52,724
Linked highlighting basically the
building blocks of how users physically

162
00:10:52,724 --> 00:10:59,295
interact with a visualization layer five
is I think, the most underappreciated

163
00:10:59,295 --> 00:11:02,084
layer and possibly the most important.

164
00:11:02,655 --> 00:11:05,145
This is semantics and interpretation.

165
00:11:05,625 --> 00:11:07,814
What does the data actually mean?

166
00:11:08,314 --> 00:11:13,084
Here's the scenario that happens in
every enterprise analytics platform,

167
00:11:13,084 --> 00:11:16,834
I have seen three different teams
build three different dashboards.

168
00:11:17,334 --> 00:11:19,795
All of them have a metric called revenue.

169
00:11:20,454 --> 00:11:22,915
None of them calculate it in the same way.

170
00:11:23,515 --> 00:11:26,545
One includes refunds and other doesn't.

171
00:11:26,964 --> 00:11:30,115
One uses net, one uses gross.

172
00:11:30,655 --> 00:11:34,015
One calculates it daily, while
other calculates it weekly.

173
00:11:34,944 --> 00:11:37,194
The semantic layer solve this.

174
00:11:38,125 --> 00:11:42,954
It's a single source of truth for
what each metric means, how it's

175
00:11:42,954 --> 00:11:45,370
calculated, and what units it uses.

176
00:11:45,870 --> 00:11:48,810
It also encodes thresholds and benchmarks.

177
00:11:49,230 --> 00:11:50,340
What's a good value?

178
00:11:50,640 --> 00:11:52,410
What triggers an alert?

179
00:11:52,860 --> 00:11:53,730
What's the target?

180
00:11:54,090 --> 00:11:58,790
These rules should live in the
system not in someone's head, and

181
00:11:58,819 --> 00:12:01,009
it creates a shared vocabulary.

182
00:12:01,550 --> 00:12:07,550
When a designer, a data engineer, and
a product manager say, churn rate, they

183
00:12:07,550 --> 00:12:09,829
should all mean exactly the same thing.

184
00:12:10,280 --> 00:12:12,439
This layer makes that possible.

185
00:12:12,939 --> 00:12:15,339
Layer six is workflow patterns.

186
00:12:15,759 --> 00:12:21,489
This is about how users actually
explore and interact with the software.

187
00:12:22,239 --> 00:12:24,819
The flows, not just the screens.

188
00:12:25,060 --> 00:12:27,159
Drill down and drill across.

189
00:12:27,669 --> 00:12:33,310
A user sees a spike in a summary chart
and wants to understand why they click

190
00:12:33,369 --> 00:12:38,259
to go deeper from country to region,
from region to city, from city to store.

191
00:12:38,739 --> 00:12:41,224
The system should have a
standard way to handle this.

192
00:12:41,724 --> 00:12:42,654
Cross filtering.

193
00:12:43,194 --> 00:12:48,294
When you select a segment in
one chart, every other chart on

194
00:12:48,294 --> 00:12:49,914
the dashboard filters to match.

195
00:12:50,604 --> 00:12:55,344
This sounds simple, but doing
it consistently and keeping the

196
00:12:55,344 --> 00:12:58,224
performance across platform is hard.

197
00:12:58,724 --> 00:13:01,994
It should be a pattern, not
something every team reinvents.

198
00:13:02,494 --> 00:13:03,724
Explore to dashboard.

199
00:13:04,384 --> 00:13:06,304
A user does some ad hoc analysis.

200
00:13:06,804 --> 00:13:10,494
Find something interesting and
wants to save it as a persistent

201
00:13:10,494 --> 00:13:12,384
dashboard that they can share.

202
00:13:13,194 --> 00:13:18,264
That transition from exploration
to artifact should be smooth and

203
00:13:18,264 --> 00:13:23,824
standardized and comparative views,
period over period, segment over

204
00:13:23,824 --> 00:13:26,254
segment, baseline versus actual.

205
00:13:26,644 --> 00:13:31,084
These are fundamental analytics workflows
and there should be patterns in the

206
00:13:31,084 --> 00:13:33,364
system, not custom implementation.

207
00:13:33,864 --> 00:13:39,145
Layer seven is governance, and I
put this at the top intentionally

208
00:13:39,204 --> 00:13:44,094
because without governance, everything
underneath is just a component library

209
00:13:44,124 --> 00:13:45,805
that will eventually drift apart.

210
00:13:46,525 --> 00:13:48,324
Governance has four pieces.

211
00:13:48,824 --> 00:13:54,705
First, an ownership model, every
metric, every component pattern

212
00:13:54,735 --> 00:13:57,194
has a named owner, not a team.

213
00:13:57,555 --> 00:13:59,385
Not a slack channel a person.

214
00:13:59,895 --> 00:14:02,295
Accountability prevents drift.

215
00:14:03,195 --> 00:14:05,025
Second, versioning discipline.

216
00:14:05,655 --> 00:14:09,975
When someone changes the definition
of a metric, that's not a bug fix.

217
00:14:10,215 --> 00:14:11,865
That's a change to history.

218
00:14:12,495 --> 00:14:17,625
It needs semantic versioning, migration
paths, and clear communication.

219
00:14:18,435 --> 00:14:23,745
Third access and sensitivity
controls, data classification,

220
00:14:23,745 --> 00:14:25,575
and role-based access.

221
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:30,450
Should be part of the design
system itself and not something you

222
00:14:30,450 --> 00:14:32,340
bolt on at the application layer.

223
00:14:32,840 --> 00:14:35,780
And fourth, a contribution workflow.

224
00:14:36,350 --> 00:14:39,320
How do new components get proposed?

225
00:14:39,410 --> 00:14:41,675
Reviewed, accepted and maintained?

226
00:14:42,500 --> 00:14:44,930
How do old ones get
deprecated and retired?

227
00:14:45,410 --> 00:14:50,000
This needs to be a defined
process with quality gates.

228
00:14:50,780 --> 00:14:53,690
So here's how it all fits together.

229
00:14:54,290 --> 00:14:55,880
Think of it as a pyramid.

230
00:14:56,570 --> 00:14:59,090
At the base, you have your design tokens.

231
00:14:59,420 --> 00:15:04,520
The widest layer, the most foundational,
everything out of depends on these values.

232
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:09,340
UI components sit on top of
the tokens, data components

233
00:15:09,340 --> 00:15:11,050
sit on top of UI components.

234
00:15:11,650 --> 00:15:12,640
And visualization.

235
00:15:12,640 --> 00:15:15,910
Primitive primitives sit
on top of data components.

236
00:15:16,780 --> 00:15:19,720
Then you get into the higher order layers.

237
00:15:20,380 --> 00:15:24,640
Semantics give meaning to
what the lower layers render.

238
00:15:25,300 --> 00:15:31,570
Workflow patterns define how users move
through the system, and governance sits

239
00:15:31,570 --> 00:15:36,820
across the top, providing control and
accountability for the whole stack.

240
00:15:37,320 --> 00:15:39,210
Each layer has a clear job.

241
00:15:39,945 --> 00:15:47,115
Each layer depends on the ones below it,
and you can adopt them incrementally.

242
00:15:47,115 --> 00:15:49,995
You don't have to build all seven at once.

243
00:15:50,505 --> 00:15:56,495
Speaking of which, let's talk about how
you'd actually adopt this foundation.

244
00:15:57,095 --> 00:15:59,885
Start with design tokens and governance.

245
00:15:59,975 --> 00:16:03,995
These are the cheapest layers
to implement, and they give

246
00:16:03,995 --> 00:16:05,225
you the highest leverage.

247
00:16:05,725 --> 00:16:08,454
Tokens give you consistency from day one.

248
00:16:09,235 --> 00:16:12,895
Governance gives you the
structure to grow without chaos.

249
00:16:13,395 --> 00:16:17,894
Data scale, invest in data components
and visualization primitives.

250
00:16:17,894 --> 00:16:21,945
Next, this is where your
users feel the pain most.

251
00:16:22,785 --> 00:16:26,985
If your table can't handle the data
and your chest are, and your charts

252
00:16:26,985 --> 00:16:30,045
are unreadable, nothing else matters.

253
00:16:30,545 --> 00:16:31,354
Semantics.

254
00:16:32,285 --> 00:16:35,434
Then unify metric definition across teams.

255
00:16:35,644 --> 00:16:39,334
This is organizational work as
much as it is technical work.

256
00:16:39,694 --> 00:16:43,834
It takes time, it requires buy-in,
and it's worth every minute.

257
00:16:44,334 --> 00:16:49,104
Then patterns, and finally,
layer in workflow patterns.

258
00:16:49,604 --> 00:16:52,269
Don't try to prescribe these upfront.

259
00:16:52,689 --> 00:16:54,874
Watch how users actually use the system.

260
00:16:55,374 --> 00:16:59,964
When you see the same flow repeated
across three teams, that's when

261
00:16:59,964 --> 00:17:01,914
you codify it as a pattern.

262
00:17:02,414 --> 00:17:06,194
So let me leave you with four
things to take back to your team.

263
00:17:06,694 --> 00:17:07,144
One.

264
00:17:07,564 --> 00:17:11,224
Three layers are not enough for analytics.

265
00:17:11,314 --> 00:17:15,574
The standard primitives
components and patterns model

266
00:17:15,634 --> 00:17:16,984
was built for consumer apps.

267
00:17:17,959 --> 00:17:23,059
It ignores data volume, semantic
complexity, and organizational governance.

268
00:17:23,629 --> 00:17:30,739
Second, seven layers give you the full
picture tokens, ui, data visualization,

269
00:17:30,769 --> 00:17:33,259
semantic workflow governance.

270
00:17:33,649 --> 00:17:37,429
Each has a clear job and
none of them are optional.

271
00:17:37,429 --> 00:17:44,329
If you want a system that actually scales
three, governance is not a nice to have.

272
00:17:44,764 --> 00:17:48,064
It's the difference between a
design system and a folder of

273
00:17:48,064 --> 00:17:50,224
components that nobody trusts.

274
00:17:50,724 --> 00:17:55,224
Ownership, versioning and access
control are what make the system real.

275
00:17:55,794 --> 00:17:58,524
And four, start at the edges.

276
00:17:58,614 --> 00:18:01,824
Work inwards, tokens and governance.

277
00:18:01,824 --> 00:18:06,444
First, data components
next, and patterns last.

278
00:18:06,714 --> 00:18:10,134
You don't need to try to
boil the ocean at once.

279
00:18:10,634 --> 00:18:15,404
The bottom line is this, build
systems that scale with your

280
00:18:15,404 --> 00:18:18,134
organization, not just with your data.

281
00:18:18,634 --> 00:18:21,004
Pick one painful layer and fix it.

282
00:18:21,034 --> 00:18:24,694
Track reuse rates, consistency
scores, and time to dashboard.

283
00:18:24,994 --> 00:18:28,744
If you can't measure whether
the system is working, you can't

284
00:18:28,744 --> 00:18:31,704
improve it and govern consistently.

285
00:18:32,124 --> 00:18:35,694
A design system without governance
is just a component library.

286
00:18:36,039 --> 00:18:37,239
With good intentions.

287
00:18:37,269 --> 00:18:39,159
So that is all I had to share.

288
00:18:39,909 --> 00:18:43,629
Thank you for listening and I would
love to hear how you're thinking

289
00:18:43,629 --> 00:18:47,889
about this in your own platforms and
what's working, what's not, where's

290
00:18:47,889 --> 00:18:49,359
you're seeing the biggest gaps.

291
00:18:49,779 --> 00:18:54,569
You can find me on LinkedIn and thanks
again and enjoy the rest of Con 42.

